Aegon, Anheuser-Busch, Societe Generale: European Equity Preview

-- B y   V i c t o r i a   T a y l o r
-- 
2011-08-11T04:00:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-10/aegon-anheuser-busch-societe-generale-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index fell 3.8 percent to 223.50. The
Stoxx 50 Index dropped 4.5 percent to 2,118.85. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark measure for nations using the euro,
decreased 6.1 percent to 2,153.77.  Aegon NV (AGN)  : The Dutch owner of U.S. insurer
Transamerica Corp. may report second-quarter net income of 339
million euros ($481 million), according to the average estimate
of 15 analysts in a Bloomberg survey. Aegon shares slid 6.2
percent to 2.97 euros.  Anheuser-Busch InBev NV (ABI)  : The world’s biggest
brewer may report second-quarter profit excluding some items of
98 cents a share, according to the average of 15 analyst
estimates compiled by Bloomberg. AB InBev shares sank 4 percent
to 35.15 euros.  Bekaert NV (BEKB BB): The world’s largest maker of steel
cord used in tires agreed to sell its specialty-films business
to a unit of Cie. de Saint-Gobain SA. Bekaert said the
transaction will reduce net debt by about 80 million euros and
result in a gain of about 10 million euros. Bekaert shares
dropped 2.4 percent to 36.22 euros.  Cie de Saint-Gobain (SGO FP): A unit of the manufacturer of
glass and construction materials agreed to buy Bekaert NV’s
specialty-films operations. The shares fell 8.1 percent to 31.43
euros.  Societe Generale (GLE)  :  France ’s second-largest bank
issued a blanket denial of “all market rumors” after
speculation that France’s creditworthiness was in doubt. The
shares fell 15 percent to 22.18 euros in Paris.  Vodafone Group Plc (VOD)  : Vodafone Group Plc said
Piramal Healthcare Ltd. agreed to buy a 5.5 percent stake in its
Indian unit for about $640 million in cash before a potential
initial public offering of the business. The shares fell 4
percent to 155.05 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
